title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Blackhawk in .38-40 and 10mm interchangeable
postcontent:
I picked this gun up as part of a trade a while back and have shot it precisely zero times since then. The previous (and original) owner said he had put perhaps 500 rounds through it in it's lifetime, the majority of them in the 10mm cylinder.

These were limited production guns, only 5,000 were made if I recall correctly. This one is in pretty fine condition, as it's been shot very little. However the previous owner did replace the button that allows the removal of the cylinder after losing the original during a shooting excursion. If you look closely you can see a slight difference in the coloring between the replacement and the guns finish.

I'm trying to slowly sell off guns that I just don't shoot. I figure it's better to get them into the hands of someone who will enjoy them and pay down my student loans with the cash.

Of course, I'm always open to trade for things that might collect less dust in the safe. I'm open to a trade for SIGs, a decent AR or AK, or quality wheel guns. It never hurts to ask about other trades, but I'm not really in the market for any hunting riles or mil surps.

Pricing for these seems to be all over the place, since they are "rare" and "collectible" (but arguably not super desirable due to the unusual rounds it accepts). I'm asking $700, which is smack in the middle of the prices I've seen in various corners of the internet.

Comes in original box (although it appears the previous owners children doodled a bit on it) with manual, a field holster and a handful of 10mm rounds.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson mod 625-2 Model of 1988 5" rare Exc. 45cal
postcontent:
A very nice weapon, highly regarded as one of the most accurate S&W revolvers made. This is an early production gun of the model 625-2, which isn't a revision, it actually started at 625-2 strangely enough! Another strange thing with the early production of this model is that the right side of the barrel is rolled/stamped with "45 CAL MODEL OF 1988", which later that same year changed to "MODEL OF 1989", since that was the actual year this model was released. Later productions within the same year were laser etched not rolled, which is the usually the more desirable of the two with collectors. There is controversy as to how many of the early guns were produced, but several sources say that only 1,500 were made with these markings. This one is in excellent shape, and comes with the original Pachy grips with the window in the bottom to allow viewing of the s/n. The safety & instruction manual is included. If I find the box I will send it also! The Ahrend grips are for show only, however if you want them I'll ask my brother what he'll take for 'em! First
$ 950.00 + shipping to your FFL takes it! I do take trades, and trades + cash so let me know what ya got and send pics too!
